nk that is the main thrust for nuclear propulsion... in space is where the real benefits will be. Politics and environment aside the best use for nuclear propulsion may be the Orion method for a heavy lift capability - 1000 ton payload.  But a SeaDragon may have been capable of about half that at 500 tons without the problems the Orion suffers in a ground launch.<br>
<br>
If I was in charge of the world, I would build a derivative of the SeaDragon to deliver the parts for an Orion to LEO.  Build it there, tug to high orbit... test the drive system on a shakedown cruise around the Earth.  Everything works fine, re-supply and head out for Mars... This would be the 80km/sec version.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ujohnfraz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_yingyang.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 169<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/15/02 4:39 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=513.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://lneilsmith.com/tools/littlelogo.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/12.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Which is safer? Flying chernobyls or big fireworks</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &gt; If I was in charge of the world, I would build a derivative<br>
of the SeaDragon to deliver the parts for an Orion to LEO.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
 I've been tossing this one around. The Sea Dragon brings ~500 tons to LEO.<br>
The Shuttle/Energia/Saturn-V class HLV delivers ~100 tons, <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>but</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> can loft a 580 ton ship to high altitude... which begins pulsing and puts ~500 tons into LEO with ridiculous delta-V for interplanetary missions.<br>
 I haven't looked at the numbers of the Sea Dragon, but could it deliver, say, a few thousand tons to a high ballistic bounce into the upper atmosphere?<br>
<br>
 We have a picture but no detail of a 20 meter Orion upper stage for &quot;post Saturn booster&quot;. No idea of its mass.<br>
<br>
It all depends on whether such a thing as a &quot;clean&quot; sub-kilotonne bomb could be made, and if even that could be allowed at ~80km altitude.<br>
<br>
 So, barring the single-HLV ship, we have several choices; (dependant on availabillity of a ~20 meter, ~500 ton to LEO booster) <br>
5+Saturn-V class HLVs to put a 500 ton Orion into LEO.<br>
5+ Sea-Dragon type HLVs to put a 2500 ton orion into LEO.<br>
<br>
 BTW, the Orion ground launch was supposedly for ~10,000 tons. Nothing chemical does that. Sea Dragon takes a while!<br>
<br>
 Good points about space use being where nuclear really shines. Granted, if safety <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> and</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> useful cargo load could <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> both</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> be guaranteed, NTR might be useful for a ground-LEO ship, but it's for cutting down the months-long interplanetary trips that it really counts.<br>
 With the best we could hope to design, we'd still get a pathetically small isp of maybe 2500, which only relatively slightly helps a ground-to LEO ship (a bit less propellant needed), but even readily do-able isp~900 drastically helps interplanetary transit times.<br>
<br>
 Then, of course, there's Orion.<br>
Stipulate: By the time you've got the mission which necesitates nuclear propulsion, <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>and</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> the political balls to get it past obstructions (driving to the launchpad over the bodies of protestors...)<br>
Result: Why not go the extra distance to get multiple HLVs (either a governmental effort spends several billion, or a private concern does it for a tenth of that) and really do a mission?!?<br>
Space-use Orion has absolutely no negative repercussions, no reasonable causes to say it absolutely can't be done (I'll bet money an HLV launch could deliver the bomb pits absolutely safely. No reasonable doubt that it could be designed to do so) and NPR does the mission <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>so much</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> better that it makes zero sense not to push for it.<br>
<br>
That leaves NTR as a good Mars hopper. You really can't beat those NIFs. (Nuclear rockets using Indigenous Fuels). Land, explore for a few days while your ship refuels itself, then hop across the planet to another site.<br>
 I also like the tri-mode NTR: O2 afterburner for perigee kick or liftoff (isp~200), NTR use as standard NERVA (900), NEP for the long haul (20,000).<br>
 It's just that if you can do this, why not use Orion, and <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>get there</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->?<br>
