No nuclear rockets were being designed as boosters. All work was towards UPPER STAGES that travel through deep space.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  There have been several deliberate and accidental crashes/explosions of nuclear rockets.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Where??<br>
When??<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  How many millions of people died as a result of that explosion Yales? Just curious.<br>
 What is the cumulative death toll so far? They had no safety systems whatsoever to prevent contamination of the environment. Nothing in place whatsoever. The death toll must have been horrendous.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
The test site, Jackass Flats, NV is located WAY out in the wilderness. Yucca Mountain, where the nuclear waste repository is next door. It is located next to the Nevada Nuclear Weapons Test Site where atom bombs were being tested at the same time.<br>
<br>
Specifically to minimize radioactive contamination, the engineers:<br>
<br>
1) used a KIWI - only a fiftieth the size of a launch booster<br>
2) the engine was located on the ground, allowing most of the particulates to fallout in the surrounding miles of desert.<br>
3) a completely fresh fuel core was used (which contains no fallout). Thus the only fallout was produced by the excursion itself. The core of a reused reactor, in flight, would contain stupendously more fallout.<br>
<br>
Even then, the radiation from the excursion and subsequent fallout cloud, would have been immediately lethal. (Radiation reached 1,000 rads!) Those at a distance where the fallout cloud passed would have increased risk of health effects.<br>
The cloud was detected all the way on the west coast.<br>
<br>
Jackass Flats is on the DOE super cleanup list of radiation.<br>
Whether the test hurt anybody can never be known. The much greater quantities of fallout from bomb testing would mask any effect.<br>
 <br>
<br>
yale<br>
