Concentrating on upper stage/interplanetary usage of nuclear rockets and not attempting to develop launch vehicles was a decision taken way back in the 50s-60s (and in secret). It was determined that operational encumberances and hazards made them unsuitable. The big F-1 engine running on Liq. Hydrogen and LOX was chosen as the path rather then a nuclear engine running on straight liquid Hydrogen. The chemical explosion risks are similar (a point ignored in the title of this thread), but there is no added radiation environment to deal with. <br>
<br>
An example of the added complexity of even normal operations with a launch booster is seen in the Gemini 6a scenario.<br>
Back in the mid-60's, Gemini/TitanII 6a fired up its engines for launch. Right off, due to a tiny dustcap not having been removed, the engines shutdown. Altho downright scary when it happened, the problem was quickly fixed and 3 days later the astronauts left Earth. If it were a nuclear booster, after shutdown, the reactor, having gone critical, would be radiating torrents of intensly penetrating radiation and a huge thermal output requiring cooling. A medium-sized nuclear booster (Titan 4 size) would have a fission product buildup equal to the exploded KIWI above in only 2.5 seconds of engine fire.<br>
<br>
It would not be a case of escorting the astronauts off in 90 minutes and topping off the tanks after a quick fix. like the Gemini.<br>
<br>
Currently NASA (as explained previously) has adopted the protocols in the space debris guidelines, and the UN priniciples for nuclear reactor in space usage. (Both of which require reactors only going critical in safe orbit or above)<br>
Having an accident during a launch dumping the equal to the UKs nuclear power industry into the bioshere is not a desireable thing. NASA is committed to these goals. And while the future may hold many mysterious things, for the foreseeable future launchers are not the way.<br>
<br>
For a good but, brief outline of the chronologies and decision-making process in the development and production of nuclear propulsion see the always excellent Astronautix.com<br>
(see also the great series at FAS)<br>
<br>
<br>
yale<br>
