1) A reused fission launcher is the equivalent of ~50 atomic powerplants in output. An accident at initial boost would be a catastrophe. Chernobyl, which vented less then 1% fission inventory required agricultural restrictions for a distance equal to New York to San Francisco. These boosters are 50 times the output.<br>
<br>
2) The greater danger is the failure to reach good orbit. This would result in the machine reentering ANYWHERE and vaporizing into the biosphere, either in part or total, with the remainder crashing and blanketing a wide swath. The radioactive debris field of the tiny soviet reactor that reentered over northwester canada covered 30,000 square miles.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  A reactor difficulty is not even comparable to the smallest nuke going off. As long as the launch site is away from inhabited areas the danger is acceptable in my opinion<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->A single power reactor contains the fallout of between 1,000 and 2,000 Hiroshima-sized atomic bombs. Don't forget that an atomic bomb fissions a core of about 5 kilograms, and a reactor fissions a core containing 2 TONS of U235. A nuclear booster has a fission output equal to ~50 power reactors.<br>
