Those who died from Chernobyl were entirely staff at the plant. Less than 30 all told. Any other figure is trumped up half baked gutter science. The required agricultural restrictions were probably way out of proportion to the scale of the emergency in an effort to appease nuclearphobes. Going way overboard in an effort to be seen as dealing with the high profile event.<br>
Fifty hiroshimas in the sky would be nothing. Hiroshima was a groundburst detonation which sucked thousands of tons of dust into its fireball, irradiated it and then dumped it as fallout on the citizens of Japan. High in the atmosphere there is almost nothing to irradiate except extremely thin atmospheric dust and vapour. Only the rocket schrapnel itself can absorb much radiation. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> The greater danger is the failure to reach good orbit. This would result in the machine reentering ANYWHERE and vaporizing into the biosphere, either in part or total, with the remainder crashing and blanketing a wide swath. The radioactive debris field of the tiny soviet reactor that reentered over northwester canada covered 30,000 square miles.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
So it was extremely thin on the ground. Sounds like a good idea if we increase the area by ensuring the ship is disintegrated in such an emergency. That way the radiation will be too diffuse to harm anything. Thanks for the contribution. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> A single power reactor contains the fallout of between 1,000 and 2,000 Hiroshima-sized atomic bombs. Don't forget that an atomic bomb fissions a core of about 5 kilograms, and a reactor fissions a core containing 2 TONS of U235. A nuclear booster has a fission output equal to ~50 power reactors.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Be a shame to waste such a large amount of useful fuel. We'd better make sure it crashes to the sea intact so we can stick it straight into another rocket.<br>
